  "prompt": "What is the rules/law of the custody of the children after divorcing in your country?",
  "response": "In the United States, child custody laws vary by state, but they generally follow similar principles. Here\u2019s an overview of the common rules and practices:\n\n### Types of Custody:\n1. **Physical Custody**: Refers to where the child lives. It can be:\n   - **Sole Physical Custody**: The child lives primarily with one parent.\n   - **Joint Physical Custody**: The child spends significant time with both parents.\n\n2. **Legal Custody**: Refers to the right to make major decisions about the child\u2019s upbringing (e.g., education, healthcare, religion). It can be:\n   - **Sole Legal Custody**: One parent has the authority to make these decisions.\n   - **Joint Legal Custody**: Both parents share decision-making responsibilities.\n\n### Determining Custody:\nCourts prioritize the **best interests of the child** when making custody decisions. Factors considered include:\n- The child\u2019s age, health, and emotional ties to each parent.\n- Each parent\u2019s ability to provide a stable and loving environment.\n- The child\u2019s relationship with siblings and other family members.\n- The child\u2019s adjustment to home, school, and community.\n- The parents\u2019 physical and mental health.\n- The child\u2019s preference, depending on their age and maturity.\n- History of domestic violence, abuse, or neglect.\n\n### Custody Arrangements:\n- **Primary Custody**: One parent has the child most of the time.\n- **Shared Custody**: The child spends substantial time with both parents (e.g., 50/50 or 60/40 split).\n- **Visitation Rights**: If one parent has sole physical custody, the other parent typically has visitation rights.\n\n### Child Support:\nChild support is often determined based on:\n- Each parent\u2019s income.\n- The amount of time the child spends with each parent.\n- The child\u2019s needs (e.g., education, healthcare).\n\n### Enforcement and Modification:\n- Custody arrangements can be enforced or modified if there\u2019s a significant change in circumstances (e.g., relocation, job loss, remarriage).\n\n### Mediation and Cooperation:\nMany states require parents to attempt mediation or cooperation to resolve custody disputes before going to court.\n\nFor specific details, consult your state\u2019s family law statutes or a family law attorney.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
